<subSubSection lastPageId="57" lastPageNumber="1202" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="56.[151,1060,951,1157]" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201">
A d d i t i o n a l m a t e r i a l e x a m i n e d (
<figureCitation box="[692,757,1087,1109]" captionStart="Figs 99" captionStartId="91.[151,191,1415,1437]" captionTargetBox="[163,1054,215,1396]" captionTargetId="figure-10@91.[153,1059,205,1404]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="Figs 99. Approximate distribution of species as noted." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5039192" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5039192/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201">Fig. 99</figureCitation>
): In addition to the 
<typeStatus box="[956,1038,1087,1109]" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201">lectotype</typeStatus>
, I examined 
<specimenCount box="[290,400,1111,1133]" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201" type="generic">6 specimens</specimenCount>
from: 
<collectingCountry box="[465,509,1111,1132]" name="Peru" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201">Peru</collectingCountry>
: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[519,745,1111,1133]" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201">Provincia de San Marti</emphasis>
n, Tarapoto,?-V-VIII-1886, M. de Mathan, Specimens are deposited in: BMNH, MNHN, and WOPC.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="56.[151,1060,1170,1277]" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201">D i a g n o s i s: Forebody, antennae, pterothorax, legs, and abdomen castaneous; elytra mostly castaneous, each elytron with 4 yellow markings, one covering elytral base, one large, triangular conjoined with epipleural margin just anterior to elytral middle, one short, oblique line just behind elytral middle near sutural margin, one oval marking near elytral apex.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="56.[151,1059,1291,1455]" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201">
R e d e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 
<quantity box="[555,639,1292,1313]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.3" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201" unit="mm" value="8.3">8.3 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity box="[722,808,1292,1313]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[963,1052,1291,1313]" captionStart="Figs 168-171" captionStartId="109.[151,191,1495,1517]" captionTargetBox="[154,1062,205,1486]" captionTargetId="figure-27@109.[154,1062,205,1486]" captionTargetPageId="109" captionText="Figs 168-171. Habitus. Priocera theresae (168), P. trinotata (169), P. trituberosa nov.sp. (170), P. uncinata (171)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5038952" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5038952/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201">Fig. 168</figureCitation>
. Head: Frons narrower than length of antennal pedicel, EW/FW 50/5. Thorax: Pronotum finely punctate, with 2 tumescenses (PW/PL 88/135); elytral disc sculptured with asetiferous punctures, latter seriate in basal 1/2, absent in apical 1/2, elytral apex rounded (EL/EW 340/60); metathoracic femur gradually increasing in diameter to femoral apex. Abdomen: Aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[424,503,1433,1455]" captionStart="Figs 70-78" captionStartId="77.[151,191,1539,1561]" captionTargetBox="[228,989,200,1532]" captionTargetId="figure-51@77.[228,989,200,1532]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="Figs 70-78. Aedeagus. Priocera quadrigibbosa (70), P.quadrinotata (71), P. spinosa (72), P. stictica (73), P. strigicollis (74), P. strigilla (75), P. theresae (76), P. trinotata (77), P. uncinata (78)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5038888" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5038888/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201">Fig. 75.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="56.[151,1058,1469,1519]" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201">
V a r i a t i o n: Size: Length 8.3-10.0 mm; width 
<quantity box="[676,796,1469,1491]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="2.2" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201" unit="mm" value="2.0" valueMax="2.2" valueMin="1.8">1.8-2.2 mm</quantity>
. Except for body size, the specimens examined are quite homogeneous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="56.[151,1058,1534,1583]" pageId="56" pageNumber="1201">N a t u r a l h i s t o r y: Specimens were collected during a time between May and August.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1058,211,263]" pageId="57" pageNumber="1202">
N o t e s: Although the 
<typeStatus box="[422,466,212,233]" pageId="57" pageNumber="1202">type</typeStatus>
was examined, the description is based on a homotype specimen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
